<HEADLINE>
FT  05 APR 94 / Slovakia: A tumultuous three years
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Apr 1991: Vladimir Meciar, former state enterprise lawyer who became prime
minister of Slovakia after Czechoslovakia's November 1989 'velvet
revolution', forced out of office after parliamentary revolt.
June 1992: Meciar sweeps back to power at head of Movement for a Democratic
Slovakia (HZDS) and starts talks with Czech Premier Vaclav Klaus about
greater autonomy just short of independence. Klaus rejects proposals and
both sides begin divorce proceedings.
Jan 1, 1993: Slovakia, under Hungarian rule until 1918 and a neo-Nazi puppet
state during second world war, achieves independence. Michal Kovac becomes
first president.
Feb 1993: Slovak currency separates from Czech currency, followed by
devaluation, a 10 per cent import surcharge and other measures to shore up
economy afflicted by rising unemployment and inflation.
Jan-Mar 1994: Progressive deterioration in relations between President Kovac
and the Meciar government, which Kovac accused of divisiveness, abuse of
power and corruption.
Mar 11: Meciar resigns after 78-2 no-confidence vote with 70 abstentions.
Mar 14: Jozef Moravcik becomes prime minister of interim coalition
government until elections on September 30.
</TEXT>
