FT  05 APR 94 / Nigeria accused over drugs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GEORGE GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The US State Department yesterday labelled Nigeria as a major drug
trafficking country, bringing an immediate halt to US aid, writes George
Graham in Washington.
Nigeria joins Burma, Iran and Syria on the State Department's list of major
drug producing or trafficking countries that are failing to co-operate in
international drug control efforts.
The US suspended most of its Dollars 32m aid programme to Nigeria last year,
after military leaders annulled a presidential election and seized power.
Under the terms of the Foreign Assistance Act, it will now also deny
Export-Import Bank financing and vote against loans to Nigeria from the
multilateral development banks. Mr Robert Gelbard, assistant secretary of
state for international narcotics affairs, said Nigerian drug couriers
accounted for 35 to 40 per cent of the heroin coming into the US.
