<HEADLINE>
FT  05 APR 94 / Devaluation fears batter Turkish lira: Currency chaos
presages austerity package
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN MURRAY BROWN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Turkey's currency markets were in chaos again yesterday, with the lira
falling by more than 10 per cent in the interbank market on the eve of an
announcement of the government's long-awaited austerity package.
The dollar was trading at TL30,500 in the interbank market, compared with a
closing rate on Friday of TL27,000, as banks rushed to close their foreign
exchange positions amid rumours the package could include another
devaluation, following the 12 per cent realignment on January 26. The
Central Bank's opening price yesterday was TL22,500 to the dollar.
Mrs Tansu Ciller, the prime minister, is expected to unveil a package of
reforms today to restore market confidence in her economic management and
curb the fiscal deficit which is running at 17 per cent of GNP.
Last month's local elections, which saw Mrs Ciller's True Path party squeeze
a narrow victory, strengthened the prime minister's hand, but it remains to
be seen whether she has the courage to administer the far-reaching changes
most economists say are now needed.
The reforms are understood to include measures aimed at reducing foreign
exchange holdings in an attempt to undercut the speculators. The rush for
foreign exchange yesterday underlines banks' concern that the government
will make it more costly to hold foreign exchange by raising the statutory
amounts banks must lodge with the Central Bank as reserve requirements. In
addition, many banks were trying to close foreign exchange open positions.
Interbank rates have risen as high as 1,000 per cent in the last 10 days,
but have since fallen back.
Rates yesterday were about 250 per cent.
In a further indication of the government's desperate search for cash, the
Treasury this week took the unprecedented step of issuing bills with an
interest rate of 125 per cent through branches of the Turkish state telecom
company.
Turkish newspapers reported the package, which will apply for six months,
would include job cuts in overstaffed public sector industries, price rises
for state sector industry products, faster privatisation, an investment
freeze, and increases in value added tax.
However, some economists suggest this will be insufficient to curb growth
and squeeze inflation, which reached an annualised 73.6 per cent in March,
according to figures announced by the state statistics department yesterday.
Tax and privatisation revenues have been lower than expected and the earlier
devaluation has added to foreign debt servicing costs. Central Bank reserves
are about Dollars 3.2bn (Pounds 2.19bn).
Confidence has been further damaged by the decision of US rating agencies to
downgrade twice since the start of the year, and by the Treasury's decision
to pull its recent Dollars 750m global bond.
</TEXT>
