<HEADLINE>
FT  05 APR 94 / US stocks fall sharply amid fears of rate rise
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP COGGAN and FRANK MCGURTY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LONDON, NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Shares on Wall Street fell sharply yesterday in response to worries that
robust US economic growth reported on Friday would make interest rate rises
more likely.
However, fears of a Wall Street collapse proved unfounded. The Dow Jones
Industrial Average dropped 83 points to 3,552 in early trading but then
rallied to close 42.61 points lower on the day at 3,593.35.
Just before the close of trading, the White House sought to calm nervous
investors. President Bill Clinton, speaking in Cleveland, Ohio, said he
thought the reaction in the markets to Friday's jobs data was overdone and
predicted interest rates would fall. 'I would encourage the American people
not to overreact,' he said.
US stock markets had been closed on Good Friday and yesterday was the first
chance for share traders to react to Friday's announcement of a 456,000
increase in non-farm payrolls in March.
The rise, the largest monthly increase since October 1987, indicated the US
economy was growing strongly and raised fears the Federal Reserve Bank would
find it necessary to push up interest rates again.
The Fed has increased short-term rates from 3 to 3.5 per cent in two moves
since early February. Since the first increase in short rates, on February
4, bond and share prices have fallen around the world.
While share prices recovered late in the day, the bond market fell sharply
amid heavy trading. The renewed fall, which pushed the yield on the
benchmark 30-year government bond up to 7.41 per cent, was prompted by
technical factors and was not linked to any fresh economic news or the
behaviour of the stock market.
The 30-year government bond was down nearly 1 3/4 points on the day, having
already fallen 1 1/2 points in thin holiday trading last Friday in reaction
to the jobs data.
Early today, the Tokyo market opened firmer, with the Nikkei 225 index
rising more than 130 points to 19,257 within the first half hour of trading.
However, yesterday's nervousness on Wall Street was expected to set the tone
for stock markets in London, Paris and Frankfurt, which resume trading today
after the Easter holiday.
Traders expect further weakness in London shares. The FT-SE 100 index, which
closed on Thursday at 3,086.4, is already 12.4 per cent down from its peak
recorded on February 2.
When the Dow fell 50 points at the start of yesterday's trading,
restrictions on program trading were imposed, under New York Stock Exchange
rules.
However, there was no sense of panic and mutual fund management group
Fidelity reported little sign of selling by private investors.
Wall Street's weakness prompted heavy falls in several Latin American
markets. Mexican stock prices ended more than 6 per cent down and Brazilian
shares fell more than 10 per cent.
Earlier, in anticipation of the fall on Wall Street, share prices in the
rest of the world edged lower.
Most European stock markets were closed for the day, although the Madrid
general index fell 2.9 per cent to a low for the year.
Asian stock markets mostly ended down, with traders nervous ahead of Wall
Street's opening. Malaysia, Singapore and Thailand recorded falls of between
2 and 3.3 per cent.
