<HEADLINE>
FT  02 APR 94 / Television (Saturday): Meatiest dishes to be found in
restaurants
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
This is a good day for staying as far away as possible from the television
screen: up a mountain, out on an estuary, or tucked into a nice little
Anglo-Italian restaurant eating something meaty with the currently
ubiquitous onion marmalade perhaps. Start with pasta because the British are
now so much better at cooking it: al dente is more common today than boiled
slimy, and real potato gnocchi . . . whoops, sorry, television.
For those with flu or babysitting obligations the trick is to hunt around
the edges of all the weekend rubbish and Easter treats. BBC2 promises Monty
Python's Fligender Zirkus, a special episode of the famous series, made for
German television and not shown in Britain since 1973. All the chaps are
featured including John Cleese and Michael Palin, as is Connie Booth who
went on to create 'Fawlty Towers' with Cleese (5.35 BBC2). A little later
BBC2 shows the semi-final for brass players in the Young Musician Of The
Year competition (7.05).
The late Dieter Plage, one of the world's greatest wildlife cameramen,
followed in the footsteps of the explorer Wilfred Thesiger, penetrating the
hot and desolate regions of Ethiopia, to make 'Forbidden Desert Of The
Danakil' in Channel 4's Kingdoms In Conflict series (8.00).
BBC2 is running a series called Arena Relics which today features 'Curse Of
The Firebeetle'. Described as 'a spaghetti western for the 1990s' and set
against the civil war in Peru, this tells the story of Ortiz, a grave robber
who happens upon the huge golden shield of the ancient sun god, Atahualpa,
and sets off for Lima to sell it (9.10 BBC2).
</TEXT>
