<HEADLINE>
FT  02 APR 94 / World Stock Markets (America): Dow fights back after heavy
morning deficit
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By FRANK MCGURTY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
US blue-chip stocks ended with modest gains on Thursday after another
buffeting from an unstable bond market, writes Frank McGurty in New York.
The Dow Jones Industrial Average closed 9.22 better at 3,635.97, after
fighting back from a 67-point deficit at mid-morning. The final push into
positive territory came only about an hour before the close, as a burst of
program-guided buying, coinciding with the end of trading in the first
quarter, lifted the bellwether index by about 30 points.
The more broadly based Standard &amp; Poor's 500 also reversed course during the
session. It climbed back from a six point decline to end 0.21 better at
445.76; but declining issues outnumbered advances by 1,532 to 738.
For a second consecutive day, activity was hectic, as portfolio managers
sought to square positions before their books closed for the quarter. NYSE
volume reached 398m shares, topping the previous day's level of 390m. The
American SE composite ended 2.43 lower at 443.11, and the Nasdaq composite
down 1.45 at 743.46.
It was an appropriate end to a week of turmoil. After a net loss of 147
points since Monday's opening, confidence was in short supply when investors
began the last session before the Easter three-day holiday.
Share prices were already slipping by mid-morning, when the Chicago
Association of Purchasing Management released its March index of business
activity. The data were received badly. Not only did the index indicate a
overall surge of activity in the region, but more importantly for the
inflation-sensitive bond market, the report's prices-paid component showed a
big rise.
In response Treasury prices, especially on the long end of the yield curve,
dropped precipitously, triggering frenzied selling in stocks. Within an
hour, however, share prices stabilised amid a cross-current of
program-driven trades.
As the day progressed, buyers finally trickled back into the Treasury
market, tempted by low prices. In equities,
bargain hunters snapped up some of Dow components battered earlier in the
week. Caterpillar recovered Dollars 3 1/8 to Dollars 112 and Allied Signal
Dollars 2 3/8 to Dollars 36 5/8 . JP Morgan gained Dollars 2 1/8 to Dollars
62 5/8 , McDonald's Dollars 1 to Dollars 56 7/8 and IBM Dollars 1 to Dollars
54.
The Dow transportation index, hammered over the past week, slipped a further
3.31 to 1,635.19. Airline stocks held up well, but trucking issues were
weak, with the expiration of a pivotal labour contract only hours away and
talks between union representatives and management stalled.
On the Nasdaq, Microsoft improved Dollars 1 1/8 and Intel gained Dollars 1
1/4 to Dollars 67 1/2 . But Pyramid Technology sank Dollars 3 7/8 to 7 7/8
after a profits warning.
Canada
Toronto stocks pulled out of another steep slide in late trading and ended
mixed to positive bias after falling for six consecutive sessions. The TSE-
300 composite index finished a busy session 15.71 points higher at 4,329.62.
Volume was 80.44m shares valued at CDollars 1.0bn.
Strong bank stocks, golds, a rebound in debt markets and bargain-hunting
combined to offer a late lift. The gold and silver index climbed by 233.46,
or 2.2 per cent to 10,778.81 after a solid rally in gold prices. Comex gold
closed up a sharp USDollars 5.70 at Dollars 394.30 per ounce, after bouncing
off a two-and-a-half-month high of Dollars 396.50.
</TEXT>
