<HEADLINE>
FT  02 APR 94 / World Stock Markets (Asia Pacific): Nikkei in modest
recovery after Thursday's setback
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EMIKO TERAZONO
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
A sharp rise in the yen hurt share prices on Thursday, but the Nikkei
regained some ground yesterday on buying by dealers and individuals, writes
Emiko Terazono in Tokyo.
The Nikkei 225 index, which plunged 447.99, or 2.3 per cent, to 19,111.92 on
Thursday, firmed yesterday by 165.24 to 19,277.16. after a low of 19,161.63
and a high of 19,378.08.
The 225 was down 2.8 per cent on the week. Wednesday's fall on Wall Street
and fears over mounting US-Japan tensions over trade, which depressed
investors' confidence, subsided as the New York stock market regained some
ground overnight.
The Topix index of all first section stocks, which fell 25.01 to 1,563.21
Thursday, ended up 7.97 to 1,571.18, while the Nikkei 300 rose 1.38 to
287.11 following a 5.26 point decline the previous day. Volume was 230m
shares, against 305m. Gainers led losers by 643 to 361 with 160 unchanged.
Analysts expect the current volatility in share prices to continue due to
the uncertainty of yen movements against the dollar, and turmoil on the
political front.
On the trading floor, mobile phone related issues were higher. Kenwood, the
most active issue of the day, rose Y6 to Y996.
Fuji Photo Film fell Y90 to Y2,200 and Konica lost Y8 to Y630 on a
preliminary decision by the US to impose anti-dumping duties on their
products.
In Osaka, the OSE average, which fell 254.78 to 21,495.30 on Thursday, rose
60.85 to 21,556.15 in volume of 15.1m shares.
Roundup
The region's markets were upset by the sharp fall on Wall Street on
Wednesday. Manila was closed on Thursday and Friday. Seoul, Taiwan, Kuala
Lumpur and Bangkok were open on Friday, Taiwan reacting most strongly to the
Dow's late recovery on Thursday.
HONG KONG's losses were trimmed by a late round of buying as news that Li
Ka-shing's Cheung Kong Group had bought a large site at a government land
auction was seen as a vote of confidence.
The Hang Seng index finished 202.30 down at 9,029.91, down 2.2 per cent on
the day and the week. Turnover remained scant at HKDollars 4.51bn.
Hongkong Land, 10 cents higher at HKDollars 22.60, bucked the downward
trend. AUSTRALIA saw its sixth straight fall, to its lowest since December
1993. The All Ordinaries index lost 39.30 at 2,053.1 down 4.6 per cent on
the week, in turnover of ADollars 395m.
Blue chips led the fall, with BHP down 48 cents, or 2.8 per cent, at
ADollars 16.48 and News Corp 25 cents at ADollars 8.95.
TAIWAN fell back 1.3 per cent on Thursday, but recovered most of that
yesterday when the weighted index rose 59.65 to 5,308.87, 0.8 per cent down
on the week. Turnover was TDollars 34bn.
KUALA LUMPUR took its lead from Wall Street, ignoring a Bank Negara's
forecast of sustained economic growth and its smaller-than-expected losses
on foreign exchange operations. The composite index, which lost 10.05 on
Thursday, picked up 7.22 to 952.72 yesterday, 1.8 per cent down on the week.
SINGAPORE was cautious about developments abroad and the Straits Times
Industrial index ended 47.49 or 2.2 per cent lower at 2,080.90 lower in
quiet trading ahead of the long weekend, little changed on the week.
KARACHI declined on profit-taking, the KSE 100-share index falling 23.24 to
2,540.46. Losers led gainers 112 to 237.
