<HEADLINE>
FT  02 APR 94 / London Stock Exchange: Shares give ground in a volatile
trading session - Market report
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TERRY BYLAND, UK Stock Market Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The final trading session for the first quarter of 1994 saw UK stocks slip
lower in volatile trading ahead of the Easter weekend. With most European
financial markets closed until Tuesday, investors were waiting cautiously to
see how Tokyo and Wall Street would react to the US jobless data expected on
Friday.
Plunging sharply at the opening, after Wall Street had suffered its largest
daily fall for the year, London stocks steadied in the Footsie 3,061 area,
with the help of firmer bond markets across Europe.
Recovery was very uncertain, however, when the pound came under pressure
again on nervousness regarding the political outlook for Mr John Major, the
UK prime minister.
The market turned better when gilts responded favourably to comments on the
UK economy from Mr Kenneth Clarke, the chancellor of the exchequer.
Encouraged also by good company results in the building sector, the FT-SE
Index moved into positive territory, and was within seven points of the
3,100 mark in early afternoon. A cut in the Bank of France intervention rate
steadied nervousness on the interest rate front.
However, the mood changed very quickly when both the Dow Average and US
Federal bonds turned off after a firm start to the new trading session in
New York. The Footsie slipped back to show a fall of nearly 10 points before
rallying yet again.
The closing reading put the FT-SE Index at 3,086.4 for a net loss on the day
of 6 points. The FT-SE Mid 250 Index fell 14.2 to 3,752.9. Seaq volume of
725.6m shares compared with 773m in the previous session, when retail
business jumped sharply to return a worth of Pounds 1.76bn.
Hopes that UK markets can disengage from the US were dented by the readiness
with which the Footsie reacted to bearish movements in the Dow Average. Some
analysts warned that selling was inhibited by the the end of the trading
quarter and that the London market was much more nervous than it might
appear.
'1987 re-visited,' was the title of the week's strategy note from Mr
Nicholas Knight of Nomura Research, once the bull but now the bear of the
London stock market. He sees the Dow Average at 3,200 and the Footsie at
2,800 in the near term. He believes that a further cut in UK base rates is
almost inevitable on political grounds but should be taken as the final
signal to sell equities.
Volatility has become the keynote of both equities and gilts at present. The
FT-SE Index travelled through a range of more than 30 points again yesterday
to show a loss on the week of around 1.4 per cent on the week. Government
bonds, although  1/2 point better at the longer end yesterday, have suffered
similar changeability which has prompted hints of large losses by some
trading firms.
The closing picture on the stock market was somewhat mixed, with special
situations providing most of the highlights. Firmness among the store and
retail issues was somewhat deceptive, with both Kingfisher and GUS moving
higher against the market trend. The blue chip multinational stocks were
unsettled by uncertainty over the US dollar and the prospect of an extended
weekend break in the London market.
</TEXT>
