<HEADLINE>
FT  02 APR 94 / Child agency faces new probe
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The operations of the Child Support Agency may soon come under fresh
scrutiny by MPs less than three months after its working methods were
changed.
The Commons social security committee will decide shortly whether to
investigate the controversial agency.
Some Tories favour delaying such a probe until later in the year on the
grounds that the new rules have not been in effect long enough for firm
conclusions to be drawn.
Mr Frank Field, the committee's Labour chairman, is thought to be keen to
press ahead. With the issue continuing to generate a great deal of mail and
many complaints at constituency advice surgeries, it is still high on most
MPs' lists of concerns.
Although Mr John Major, the prime minister, has underlined the government's
determination not to be stampeded into ordering further changes to the rules
governing the agency, there is a widespread acceptance in Whitehall that
more fine-tuning may eventually be needed.
The changes, introduced in February, enabled absent fathers facing big
increases in maintenance payments to pay the bills in stages over 18 months
and ensured that addresses of separated parents were not disclosed.
</TEXT>
