FT  02 APR 94 / World Bank warns on MFN
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Any US move to strip China of its Most Favoured Nation trading status, due
to human rights concerns, could have 'disastrous' consequences for both
nations, a World Bank study warned. It said Chinese exports to the US could
be cut by 42-96 per cent if President Bill Clinton decided not to renew MFN
status for China in June. American consumers could also pay Dollars 14bn
(Pounds 9.5bn) a year more for costlier substitutes for Chinese products. Mr
Clinton last year demanded significant progress from China on human rights
as a condition for renewing trade benefits this year.
