<HEADLINE>
FT  02 APR 94 / Soccer clubs may win reprieve for stadium terraces
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Ministers may drop the requirement for Britain's leading football clubs to
have all-seater stadiums by August in a move that could mean a reprieve for
terrace culture.
They are considering whether to extend this summer's deadline - which in
England includes Premiership and First Division clubs - on a case-by-case
basis, and whether to combine this with a law change to remove the
all-seater requirement.
This would be part of a reform of the three acts governing sports grounds,
which ministers would like rationalised into one under wider deregulation
moves.
If the proposed reform makes it on to the 1994-95 legislative timetable, as
the Department of National Heritage is understood to have requested, this
could mean a permanent reprieve for some terraces - with their tradition of
songs and chants and cheaper admission prices.
But the department said last night that the fact that the three acts might
be rationalised should not lead people to assume the government was
necessarily going to change its policy.
Although several clubs are struggling to meet the August deadline, such a
policy reversal would probably be viewed dimly by those that have already
spent heavily to upgrade their grounds. The apparent softening of the
government's stance stems from two main factors:
A growing feeling that the Taylor report into the 1989 Hillsborough
disaster, which led to the all-seater requirement, took an understandably
but unnecessarily rigid line. Some 95 fans were crushed to death on the
terraces at the Sheffield ground.
Improvements in ground safety technology. Mr Iain Sproat, national heritage
minister, is understood to have been impressed by a system that monitors
pressure around a stadium.
Mr Tom Pendry, a Labour national heritage spokesman, recently referred to
this system, saying: 'I firmly believe that, in the light of new
developments, supporters should be given the opportunity to stand in new,
safer areas.'
One club which will apply for an extension to the August deadline is
Barnsley, according to Mr Michael Spinks, general manager. The club has
planning consent for a 4,500-seater stand lifting its seating capacity to
more than 14,000, but the earliest this will open is 1995.
Rebates for sports clubs, Page 9
</TEXT>
<XX>
